,Not Recommended,296770,13304882,"Posted: 10 December, 2014",all,nusensei,"The fact that this is a handheld/mobile port is frighteningly obvious. While there is a lack of boxing games on PC, this game is not up to standard. The animations are very poor and the gameplay is poorly thought out. Career mode is very skinny with three mini-games that you can only occasionally use to train your boxer, and the title fights are insanely easy on the first circuit and insanely hard on the second circuit. Progression is really repeatiing the same low-level circuit until you can get enough cash to boost your stats to survive getting hit in the next level.The fighting mechanics lack any flow or depth. You cannot throw combinations, so boxing is simply a matter of tapping the jab or hook button. Blocking is a one-button affair, and while you can punch through a block, you don't have enough stamina to exploit it. Hit reactions are awkward - punches don't connect to the opponent, so if the opponent is staggering, your punches are sure to miss, which is very unintuitive. The counterattack system seems like something nice, but it's really just an opportunistic slow-mo which is botched by the lack of fluid fighting.The characters are all the same. There are no distinctions between boxing styles, so it's really just a slugfest. It's disappointing to see a ""Real Boxing"" title feature nothing that makes boxing real.Some other huge flaws:* Clinch mini-game has no timer. You can clinch for the entire round.* Getting up from a KO immediately goes into the fight, allowing the opponent free hits before your controls are live.* No three-knockdown rule. The AI is generally unable to come back and gets knocked down right away, but there is no way to win by TKO.In a nutshell, winning the game is merely based on when the AI ""forgets"" to block rather than any tactical gameplay."
