76561198039329770,Not Recommended,296770,14692952,"Posted: 28 February, 2015",all,MaskedHero666,"* Please note my review is based on the single player career mode only and not online play.After 3 hours played, I have to sadly give this game a negative review.Without any regret, I placed this title on my list of ""completed games"", where it was promptly uninstalled, despite me not finishing the game. This can only mean that the game was so flawed that there was nothing I could do but give it a miss and not feel guilty that it was being put on the backburner...permanently.Why?Initially I had trouble understanding how the game worked because I don't really watch boxing, nor do I ever play it in real life or in the virtual World, even though I personaly have thrown a punch or two during a pub crawl. So because I only knew the basics of boxing, it should really have meant that I would struggle in a game happily named ""Real Boxing"", but alas here is where I ran into quite a big problem.Since I was a huge novice, as expected I lost my first two matches because I was doing what I thought was ""real"" boxing. That was to try and ""mix it up"" and jab a couple of times, then try a much more potent move, wowing the crowd with a powerful KO. Instead every match seemed rather tame and while they were close affairs, I could not buy a win and quite honestly things were going as expected.During my first three career matches, I had lost two games on points and the last had ended as a draw but things were about to change...drastically. In the game I got myself a draw, I noticed I didn't have to throw so many varied punches, but just throw one particular punch, a jab - then back off a little to recover my stamina. It was a cue that I would definitely bring into my upcoming fourth match where I decided to roll with this uninspring but effecive style of boxing and went back to the ring seeking revenge with my new jabbing prowess...In my fourth match all I threw were jabs, and did so with devastating results. I got the combo count to about 3 or 4 then as my stamina wore down, I backed off and let it recover and then I just went back in and hit left and right handed jabs again and again. After each round I had landed about 40 to 60 punches and my adversary had a mere 5 to 15 each time. At the end of the match, I had a resounding unanimous victory.I then went to the gym and put all my winnings into my boxers speed and also completed the mini games which were available. After 4 matches my speed was something around 70 and by 3 hours played, it had hit the 80 mark. I had a quick footed boxer, with fleeting punches ready to lightly jab into any boxers face as if he were putting on powder with a puffy makeup brush. It was a heavily feminine style of play, but it was effective - and I was tempted to call my boxer Blue Steel.I won every single match with complete ease, all the way to the title belt!Yes you read that right...! Even though I started with two defeats and a draw, I won match after match thereafter to become the champion. So I went up a division and again put all my coins into speed and again with the same boxing style I won fight after fight all the way until I hit the uninstall button on the game.This game has a lot of fighting mechanics, but you don't need any of them. You don't need uppercuts, haymakers, strength, perks, hugging or whatever it is called when you take a nap on the other boxer, etc etc etc.You just jab and run away, and inevitably win - which some how reminded me of World of Warcraft back in 2006 when I used to ""dot and run"" with my Warlock. If you don't know what that means, then you know exactly how I felt when I first started playing this game - clueless. Yet at the end you feel like a champion and it's not because you are good, it is because the game is completely flawed.Rather than kid myself that I indeed was a ""real"" boxer, I inevitably preferred to uninstall the game. I knew I was nothing but a jabbing phoney and I just could not bring myself to win the career mode knowing that.  Who want's to be the Lance Armstrong of boxing?I know I didn't.I give this game an F, or 2 out of 10."
